        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_3",
          "href": null,
          "name": "3c33",
          "text": "The heart of good communication is a simple but profound capacity to listen. Listening requires that we not only hear the words, but also embrace, accept, and gradually let go of our own inner clamouring. We cannot truly listen if we are already reacting to and judging what is being said, while it is being said. As we explore deeper listening as a path towards understaning, we discover that it is an expansive activity. It gives us a way to perceive more directly the ways we participate in the world around us.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_4",
          "href": null,
          "name": "9d73",
          "text": "Listening, an activity we all believe we know how to do, is actually very hard to do, and requires commitment and practice. Krishnamurti, the Indian philosopher, put the challenge this way:",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_5",
          "href": null,
          "name": "6f46",
          "text": "“I do not know if you have ever examined how you listen, it doesn’t matter to what, whether to a bird, to the wind in the leaves, to the rushing waters or how you listen in a dialogue with yourself to your conversation in various relationships with your intimate friends your wife or husband. If we try to listen we find it extraordinarily difficult, because we are always projecting our opinions and ideas, our prejudices, our background, our inclinations, our impulses; when they dominate, we hardly listen to what is being said. In that state there is no value at all. One listens and therefore learns, only in a state of attention, a state of silence in which this whole background is in abeyance, is quiet; then, it seems to me, it is possible to communicate.”",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 765,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 0,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "PQ"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_6",
          "href": null,
          "name": "f563",
          "text": "— Krishnamurti, Talks and Dialogues",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 35,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 16,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "PQ"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_7",
          "href": null,
          "name": "503d",
          "text": "To listen, then, is to develop an inner silence. This is not a familiar habit for most of us. We often pay great attention to what is going on inside us, when actually what is required is a kind of disciplined self-forgetting — a letting go of the constant inner commentator and judge of what or who we are listening to. We must create a space in which listening can occur.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_8",
          "href": null,
          "name": "0d5b",
          "text": "Learning to listen begins with recognizing how you are listening now. Generally, we are not all that conscious of how we listen. You can begin to listen by listening first to yourself and to your own reactions. Try to identify what you feel more carefully and directly. Beginning with the perception of your own feelings connects you to your heart and to the heart of your experience. To learn to be present, we must learn to notice what we are feeling now.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_9",
          "href": null,
          "name": "cb32",
          "text": "Some Elements of Active Listening",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 33,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 0,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "STRONG",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "H4"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_10",
          "href": null,
          "name": "9d92",
          "text": "Liberate our Mind: We can hardly advance a truly efficient communication if our starting point is not an active listening. And to listen, in addition to applying our senses, we have to liberate our mind –of our preoccupations, prejudices, assumptions, etc. Our mind is so full of “things” that we are unable to listen and take on what others try to tell us. Only a deep inner silence allows us to be fully open to other people’s voices.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 19,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 0,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "STRONG",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_11",
          "href": null,
          "name": "6753",
          "text": "Empathize: Listening is not only hearing words, but being open, accepting, and empathizing. Besides trying to understand what people are saying, you should pay attention to your perceptions and emotions and to the context of who is speaking. To listen effectively you need to be humble, resist lecturing others, and instead look for connections at the level of your shared experiences.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 11,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 0,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "STRONG",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_12",
          "href": null,
          "name": "987e",
          "text": "Ask and Reformulate: Ask to clarify things, become more conscious, and allow wisdom to come out of who is speaking. Inquire into the emotional state of your partner. Ask to check if your understanding of what the speaker is saying is correct. Repeat in a positive way without judging. Reformulate without adding your own interpretation and without looking for the answers you desire.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 21,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 0,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "STRONG",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_13",
          "href": null,
          "name": "4ec3",
          "text": "Some Elements of Deep Listening",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 31,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 0,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "STRONG",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "H4"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_14",
          "href": null,
          "name": "3ba1",
          "text": "Honour People’s Boundaries: Deep listening begins with respect. To respect means, among other things, to honour people’s boundaries–to be sensitive to them without trying to push them and without wanting to adapt or convert them to our own ideas and beliefs. To respect is also not to take distance from people when they say or do something we don’t like. To respect is to understand that everybody can teach us something.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 28,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 0,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "STRONG",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_15",
          "href": null,
          "name": "7e55",
          "text": "See your Teacher in Every Person, in Every Situation: From every person, from every situation you can learn something. Your listening will be deep when you ask yourself what is there beyond your feelings, your pain, and your anger; what you can learn from what happened, and who and what is teaching you.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 54,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 0,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "STRONG",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "f6e8dd1de9bc_16",
          "href": null,
          "name": "7de0",
          "text": "Accept Difference: Everything that happens to us is part of a whole that we may not be aware of, or that we don’t fully understand. We listen deeply when we are humble and accept that we don’t have the whole truth, and need to open up to other people’s truth.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
